Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);
47345b0c-a7b3-4d11-ae60-95d83b7b4f81.2631cf7f-d1f3-477c-8df0-ee8a35cf6a70.prompt=Cluster name\: 47345b0c-a7b3-4d11-ae60-95d83b7b4f81.2b434c33-b10f-4b63-8307-85d8521a2ce3.description=
Retrieves information about the nodes that form a cluster.

Inputs\:
host - The hostname or ip address of the cluster server (e.g. w2k8cluster, 10.51.0.225).
delimiter - The delimiter for the results. The default value is ",".

Responses\:
success - The operation succeeded.
failure - Something went wrong.

Result\:
General information about the cluster nodes. The following information is returned for each node\: name, state, networks that the node belongs to and ip address of the node in each network. Each cluster network that is up will be retrieved, regardless of its role (i.e. private, public, mixed or not enabled).

Extra Results\:
clusterNodeNames - A list with the names of the nodes separated by the delimiter.
clusterNodeStates - A list with the states (i.e Up, Down, Paused, Joining, StateUnknown) of the nodes separated by the delimiter.
clusterNodeAddresses - A list with the IP addresses of the nodes separated by the delimiter. Only the addresses for networks that are up and that provide client systems with access to cluster application services are shown. 

Notes\:
1. Thanks to MS's way of building the COM interface to MS Clustering admin tools, we can't use any impersonation with it.  
Therefore, to make it work properly you have to run the Windows RAS service as an account with privileges.
2. Clean install of Windows 2008 (on the RAS machine) does not include by default msclus.dll library. To work around this issue there are 2 alternatives. The first one is to install the failover clustering feature on the machine, which will install the msclus.dll to "%systemroot%\system32\msclus.dll". The alternative is to  copy "%systemroot%\system32\msclus.dll" from a Windows Server 2003 server to the same location on the Windows 2008 (R2) machine and run "regsvr32 %systemroot%\system32\msclus.dll" (if you have a 64-bit Windows 2008 then you have to copy msclus.dll from a 64-bit Windows 2003).
3. To administer a Windows 2008 cluster you have to install RAS on a Windows 2008 machine. Backward compatibility has been broken by Microsoft, according to http\://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb756975.aspx, which means that you cannot call Cluster APIs from a Windows Server 2008 Cluster to a down-level cluster (Windows NT 4.0, Windows 2000, or Windows 2003). Also, you cannot be on a down-level client and remotely call Cluster APIs against a Windows Server 2008 node.
47345b0c-a7b3-4d11-ae60-95d83b7b4f81.321b8052-8d94-4fac-804a-07eddcee2fe9.prompt=Email content transfer encoding\: 47345b0c-a7b3-4d11-ae60-95d83b7b4f81.346d8bbb-4857-4afd-9291-5b772bd7771e.description=
Checks for any network errors.

Inputs\:
host - The host to check.
user - The username to login to host with.
password - The password for user.
outputPath - The network accessible path used by the operation to store temporary files. If not specified it points to \\host\admin$\temp\'. If this path is not accessible you should change it to use another share that the host local system account has write access to. By default, the path will have to be  changed on Windows 2000 systems.
diagnostic so far - Used to chain diagnostics together, and get one report. The output of previous diagnostics, or blank.
characterSet - The character encoding of the host computer. The default is the RAS machine's default encoding.

Responses\:
success - Diagnostic successful.
failure - Something went wrong.
connectivity failure - Connection to host may be unreliable.

Note\:
The character encoding specified in the input for characterSet must be compatible for the host and RAS systems, otherwise the command file created to execute the command becomes garbled causing an error while executing.

47345b0c-a7b3-4d11-ae60-95d83b7b4f81.5f781458-10a8-4441-9bd5-587f1e1c19f3.prompt=Enter a value for toMatch 47345b0c-a7b3-4d11-ae60-95d83b7b4f81.604b648b-b51c-457a-8e1d-02dec4b39ecc.prompt=Email character set\: 47345b0c-a7b3-4d11-ae60-95d83b7b4f81.63e8e773-7e65-4683-8405-f1e11f07d0d5.description=
Iterates through a list of values. Modifying the value of the list and delimiter inputs during iteration is not generally supported.

Inputs\:
list - The list to iterate through.
separator - A delimiter that separates elements in the list.

Returns\:
The current element of the list, if the response is has more

Responses\:
has more - Another value was in the list, and has been returned.
has no more - The iterator has gone fully through the list. This response will only be returned once per iteration through the list, a subsequent call to the Iterator will restart the Iteration through the list.
failure - failed to process the list.

Note\: Where the iterator is in the list is tracked by each step's unique id. Therefore you can iterate on the same list from multiple steps simultaneously.

WARNING\: Any step that will use the results of this Iterator operation will, by default, attempt to assign that step's inputs from a flow variable. If this is left checked, then the first element of the iterator will be used for every cycle of iteration.
47345b0c-a7b3-4d11-ae60-95d83b7b4f81.751dfb6b-0361-4431-8c7a-93420b401fdd.description=
Sends an smtp email.
 
Inputs\:
    hostname - The hostname or ip address of the smtp server.
    port - The port smtp service is listening.
    from - From email address.
    to - A delimiter separated list of email address(es) or recipients.
    cc - A delimiter separated list of email address(es) or recipients, to be placed in the CC.
    bcc - A delimiter separated list of email address(es) or recipients, to be placed in the BCC.
    subject - The email subject. If a subject spans on multiple lines, it is formatted to a single one.
    body - The body of the email.
    htmlEmail - Default value is true. The value should be true if the email is in rich text/html format. The value should be false if the email is in plain text format.
    readReceipt - Default is false. The value should be true if read receipt is required, else false.
    attachments - A deliimiter separated list of files to attach (must be full path).
    username - If SMTP authentication is needed, the username to send.
    password - The password to use.
    characterSet - The character set encoding for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is UTF-8.
    contentTransferEncoding - The content transfer encoding scheme (such as 7bit, 8bit, base64, quoted-printable etc) for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is - quoted-printable or Q Encoding.
    delimiter - A delimiter to separate the email recipients and the attachments. This input defaults to ';' if left empty.
 
Responses\:
    success - Successfully sent the email.
    failure - Failed to send the email.

Note\:
1. For special characters (East Asian, right-to-left languages, etc.) you must install the support files on your local machine.
2. For doing this on Windows go to Control Panel -> Regional and Language Options -> Language and check the options at Supplemental language support.

47345b0c-a7b3-4d11-ae60-95d83b7b4f81.description=
This flow runs a Windows diagnosis for all the hosts/nodes in a cluster and generates a report containing the diagnosis results. The report is either displayed or emailed according to the user's choice.

Inputs\:
clusterHost - The hostname or ip address of the cluster server (e.g. w2k8cluster, 10.51.0.225).
user - The username to use when authenticating with the hosts in the cluster.
password - The password to use when authenticating with the hosts in the cluster.
sendEmail - Specifies whether an email containing the results of the diagnosis will be sent or if these results will be displayed.
mailHost - The address of an SMTP server to use when sending the email.
mailUsername - If SMTP authentication is needed, the username to send.
mailPassword - If SMTP authentication is needed, the password to use.
to - The email address to send the diagnosis report to.
from - The email address the summary will appear to come from.
characterSet - The character set encoding for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is UTF-8.
contentTransferEncoding - The content transfer encoding scheme (such as 7bit, 8bit, base64, quoted-printable etc) for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is - quoted-printable or Q Encoding.
CPUUsageThreshold - Maximum acceptable percentage cpu usage.
maxBlockedThreads - Maximum acceptable number of blocked threads.
minimumTotalMemory - Minimum value of memory that this computer is expected to have.
freeMemoryThreshold - The percentage of total memory that should not be in use as a decimal.
freePagingThreshold - Number of kilobytes of paging file expected to not be in use.
maxPagesPerSecond - Maximum number of memory pages per second considered acceptable.
processList - A list of processes that should be running.
freespaceThreshold - Minimum acceptable percentage of freespace as a decimal.
outputPath - The network accessible path used by the operation to store temporary files. If not specified it points to \\host\admin$\temp\'. If this path is not accessible you should change it to use another share that the host local system account has write access to. By default, the path will have to be  changed on Windows 2000 systems.
nodesCharacterSet - The character encoding of the nodes in the cluster. The default is the RAS machine's default encoding.

Responses\:
success - The diagnosis could be performed normally.
failure - The diagnosis failed or the email could not be sent.

Results\:
failedNodes - A comma-separated list of the hosts/nodes (in the cluster) for which problems were detected.
